A new course at Harvard University this year will make all its pre-graduate students get more sleep in an effort to combat the growing macho culture of studying by caffeine driven 'whole-day sessions'.
An academic has found that students at the world's top university are often ignorant of the basic principles of how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical Faculty and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the U.S..
He was inspired to start the course after he gave a talk about the effect of sleep withdrawal on learning.
'At the end, one girl approached me and said, 'Why do they tell me this now, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had told her how important sleep is--which surprised me,' he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was presented this year for the first time, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their overall well - being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical Faculty and executive director of the university’s health services, said that the university decided to take the course after it was found that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The hourly course involves some interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dormitory, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, practice shoes and books to be told about the effect of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is influenced by lack of sleep and the importance of a sleep time routine.
In another department participants are told how long-term sleep withdrawal can increase risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
'We know it won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know--just as you have the right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,' Prof Czeisler added.
The culture of pride to 'study all day' still exists, he said, and added that modern technology and increasing pressure on students meant that sleep withdrawal is a growing problem.
To make sure that you get enough sleep of good quality, a student's 'secret weapon' should be to avoid stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said--even to avoid putting on weight, because sleep loss puts the brain in a hunger mode, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californiar studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after he walked one of his classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to work for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when they are going to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and being aware of the harmful effects of 'blue light' emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
